"""
MKT Christ in Every Verse — Romans chapters 15–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-romans-15-16.py

Source data used:
- data/translation/draft/mediating/romans.json (MKT text)
- data/interlinear/romans.json (Greek tokens for key terms)
- data/parallels/romans.json (absorbed: Ps 18:49 at 15:9, Deut 32:43 at 15:10,
  Ps 117:1 at 15:11, Isa 11:10 at 15:12, Isa 52:15 at 15:21, Gen 3:15 at 16:20)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/romans.json (chs.1–10 for style/terminology continuity)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch.15 is structured around Paul's catena of four OT citations (vv.9–12) — Ps 18:49,
  Deut 32:43, Ps 117:1, Isa 11:10 — all classified direct because Paul explicitly applies
  them to Christ's Gentile mission (the Root of Jesse / the risen Lord praising among nations).
- Ps 69:9 at v.3 is classified direct: Paul reads it as Christ's own voice bearing reproach
  for others, consistent with the NT use pattern (John 2:17, 15:25).
- Isa 52:15 at v.21 classified direct: Paul applies the Servant's mission to unevangelized
  Gentiles, treating the Servant's work as Christ's own.
- Gen 3:15 at 16:20 classified direct: the serpent-crushing promise is applied to Christ's
  victory over Satan, extending to his people through his triumph.
- Ch.16 greeting verses (vv.1–16, 21–23) are brief; the focus is the Christological
  significance of "in the Lord" / "in Christ" as the community's constitutive identity.
- The doxology (16:25–27) is the theological climax of the entire letter — classified direct
  as an explicit Christological summary.
- Continuity from chs.1–10: directness levels stated as "A direct:", "A type:", "A shadow:",
  "A theme:", "A revelation of God:".
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: The call to bear with the failings of the weak rather than please oneself is grounded in a Christological pattern Paul will make explicit in v.3. The strong who carry rather than exploit the weak enact the cruciform logic: Christ did not please himself but bore others\' reproaches. The ethical imperative is not merely social courtesy but participation in Christ\'s own pattern of self-giving.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct: Paul sets the neighbor-oriented ethic in direct opposition to self-pleasing, anticipating the explicit contrast with Christ in v.3. "Building up" (<em>oikodomē</em>) is Paul\'s characteristic term for the corporate edification of the body of Christ (1 Cor 14:12; Eph 4:12) — each member contributing to the whole as Christ gave himself for the whole.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct: Paul cites Ps 69:9 ("The insults of those who insult you have fallen on me") as Christ\'s own voice. This is the hermeneutical claim: the righteous sufferer of the Psalms finds its ultimate referent in Christ, who bore reproaches intended for others — not as a secondary application but as the fulfillment the psalm pointed toward. Christ did not please himself precisely by absorbing the hostility that belonged to sinners.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Everything written in the past was written to teach us, so that through the endurance taught in the Scriptures and the encouragement they provide we might have hope." The Scriptures\' telos is hope — the eschatological hope that Paul\'s entire argument has been building toward, grounded in Christ\'s resurrection (5:5; 8:24-25). The OT\'s Christological function is not just predictive prophecy but the formation of the hope that Christ\'s resurrection vindicates.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct: The prayer for "the same attitude of mind toward each other that Christ Jesus had" is an explicit appeal to Christ\'s own disposition as the standard for communal life. The "God who gives endurance and encouragement" is the God who enables believers to reproduce Christ\'s cruciform pattern. The unity Paul prays for is not merely sociological agreement but Christomorphic conformity (cf. Phil 2:5-8).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct: The goal of unity is "with one mind and one voice" glorifying "the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ." The designation "God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ" is Paul\'s characteristically Trinitarian framing: the Father is identified by his relationship to the Son, and the unified praise of the community participates in the Son\'s own doxology to the Father.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct: "Accept one another, then, just as Christ accepted you." The acceptance that overcomes the strong-weak, Jew-Gentile division is modeled on and motivated by Christ\'s prior acceptance of both parties. Christ\'s welcome is the basis, pattern, and measure of human welcome within the community. The dative "in order to bring praise to God" ties the communal acceptance back to the doxological goal of v.6.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct: "Christ has become a servant of the Jews (<em>diakonon peritomēs</em>) on behalf of God\'s truth, so that the promises made to the patriarchs might be confirmed." This is Paul\'s clearest statement of the incarnation\'s purpose as promise-fulfilment: Christ took on Jewish particularity in order to validate what God promised Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. The patriarchal promises (Gen 12:3; 22:18) required a Jewish Messiah — and Christ is that Messiah.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct: Paul cites Ps 18:49 ("I will praise you among the Gentiles; I will sing the praises of your name") as Christ\'s own voice in the post-resurrection mission. The risen Christ praises the Father among the Gentile nations through the believing community gathered from every nation. Paul reads the Davidic psalm Christologically: what David sang in prospect, Christ fulfills in accomplishment.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct: Deuteronomy 32:43 ("Rejoice, you Gentiles, with his people") is applied to the unified worship of Jew and Gentile in Christ. Paul reads the Song of Moses as anticipating the eschatological ingathering that Christ\'s mission accomplished — the Gentiles joining Israel\'s praise, no longer strangers to the covenants but co-participants in the one people of God (Eph 2:19).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct: Psalm 117:1 ("Praise the Lord, all you Gentiles; let all the peoples extol him") is the broadest of the four citations — a call to universal Gentile worship. Paul reads the LORD whom all nations are to praise through the lens of Christ\'s lordship, established at the resurrection (Phil 2:10-11; Rom 10:9). The universal praise the psalm commands is the universal mission that Christ\'s resurrection launched.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct: Isaiah 11:10 — "The Root of Jesse will spring up, one who will arise to rule over the nations; in him the Gentiles will hope" — is Paul\'s most explicitly messianic citation in this catena. The Root of Jesse is Christ: the Davidic shoot anticipated by Isaiah, now identifying Jesus as the one in whom Gentile hope is placed. This is the Christological anchor of the entire four-citation sequence; the others demonstrate that Gentile inclusion was always part of the divine purpose, and Isaiah 11 names the agent who accomplishes it.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct: "May the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace as you trust in him, so that you may overflow with hope by the power of the Holy Spirit." The hope, joy, and peace Paul invokes are all secured by Christ\'s resurrection (5:1-2, 10-11; 8:24-25) and distributed through the Spirit who is Christ\'s own Spirit (8:9). The God of hope is the God who raised Christ from the dead — and therefore the guarantor that hope will not disappoint (5:5).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: Paul\'s confidence in the Roman believers\' goodness, knowledge, and capacity to instruct one another reflects his conviction that Christ is forming his people through the Spirit. The qualities he names — goodness, knowledge, mutual instruction — are the Spirit\'s work (Gal 5:22; Col 3:16), which is the ongoing outworking of the Christological transformation begun in baptism (6:4). The community\'s capacity for mutual instruction is a Christological achievement.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct: Paul writes "because of the grace God gave me" — the grace of apostolic commission is specifically the grace of proclaiming Christ to the Gentiles (1:5; 12:3; 15:16). The bold reminding Paul does is not self-generated authority but the authority of the commissioned herald of Christ. The grace that grounds the boldness is Christ-given for Christ\'s purposes.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct: Paul describes himself as a <em>leitourgos</em> (liturgical minister) of Christ Jesus to the Gentiles, with "the priestly duty of proclaiming the gospel of God, so that the Gentiles might become an offering acceptable to God, sanctified by the Holy Spirit." The priestly-sacrificial language — liturgist, offering, sanctification — is applied to the Gentile mission: the Gentiles converted to Christ are the priestly offering Paul presents to God. Christ is the high priest; Paul is the ministering priest; the converted Gentiles are the acceptable sacrifice.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct: "I glory in Christ Jesus in my service to God." Paul\'s boast is entirely Christological — not his own achievements but what Christ has accomplished through him. The apostolic ministry is Christ\'s work; Paul is the instrument. The <em>kauchēsis</em> (boasting/glorying) that Paul spent chapters 3-4 dismantling as human self-commendation is here replaced by its only legitimate form: glorying in Christ alone (1 Cor 1:31).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct: "I will not venture to speak of anything except what Christ has accomplished through me in leading the Gentiles to obey God." The passive construction — Christ accomplishing through Paul — is Paul\'s consistent framing of apostolic agency (cf. Gal 2:20; Phil 1:21). The Gentile obedience that resulted is not Paul\'s achievement but Christ\'s, mediated through a commissioned herald. The mission belongs to Christ from start to finish.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct: The "signs and wonders" and "the power of the Spirit of God" that accompanied Paul\'s proclamation are Christ\'s power manifested through his apostle. The full proclamation of Christ\'s gospel from Jerusalem to Illyricum constitutes the Servant\'s mission territory (Isa 49:6) beginning to be filled — the gospel going out from Zion to the ends of the earth. Christ\'s power is the only explanation Paul offers for the geographic sweep of the mission.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct: Paul\'s pioneering ambition — to preach where Christ was not known, building on no one else\'s foundation — is shaped by Isa 52:15, quoted in v.21. The foundation Paul refuses to build on is another apostle\'s work; the only foundation he lays is Christ (1 Cor 3:11). The pioneer mission is a Christological imperative: the unreached need to hear about Christ, not hear Christ\'s name recycled where it is already known.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct: Isaiah 52:15 — "Those who were not told about him will see, and those who have not heard will understand" — applied to the Gentile mission as Christ\'s own Servant-mission extended through Paul. In its original context the verse describes the Servant\'s impact on kings who had not previously heard. Paul reads it as the mandate for mission to unevangelized Gentiles: the Christ who is the Servant has accomplished what Isaiah foresaw, and Paul\'s mission enacts that accomplishment geographically.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: Paul\'s frequent hindrance from coming to Rome was the consequence of the same pioneer calling — proclaiming Christ where he was unknown consumed the time that might have been spent visiting an already-established church. The constraint is Christological: the mission\'s priorities are Christ\'s, not Paul\'s own preferences for fellowship.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme: "No more place for me to work in these regions" — Paul\'s sense of completion in the eastern Mediterranean reflects the Christological logic of his mission: his task was to plant, not to build beyond the foundation others could complete. The long-held longing to visit Rome is set within the framework of the ongoing westward advance of Christ\'s gospel.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme: The Spain plan situates the Gentile mission within the ancient conception of "the ends of the earth" (Isa 49:6; Acts 1:8). Paul\'s westward ambition is the geographical extension of Christ\'s commission: the gospel going to the ends of the earth through a commissioned herald. Rome is not the destination but the provisioning stop on the way.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct: The journey to Jerusalem "in the service of the Lord\'s people there" — the collection Paul carries is a concrete expression of Gentile debt to Jewish believers, mediated through Christ. The material service (<em>diakonia</em>) is the outward form of the spiritual unity that Christ has created between Jew and Gentile (15:27; Eph 2:14-16). Paul goes to Jerusalem as Christ\'s minister, bearing Gentile love as an offering.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A theme: Macedonia and Achaia\'s voluntary contribution for the poor among the Lord\'s people in Jerusalem expresses the unity of the body of Christ across geography and ethnicity. The Gentile churches\' generosity toward Jewish believers is the material sign of what Christ has accomplished spiritually: the Gentiles who received spiritual blessings through Israel now return material blessing to Israel\'s poor (v.27). The collection is the enacted theology of 11:17-24.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct: "For if the Gentiles have shared in the Jews\' spiritual blessings, they owe it to the Jews to share with them their material blessings." The spiritual blessings are the covenantal blessings that came through Israel — the promises, the Messiah, the gospel — all of which the Gentiles received through Jewish channels (9:4-5; 11:17-18). The material obligation is grounded in Christological debt: Christ came from Israel, and the Gentiles received him through Israel\'s witness.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A theme: Paul\'s planned route — Jerusalem, then Spain via Rome — is framed around completing the task Christ gave him. The phrase "I have made sure they have received this contribution" reflects Paul\'s apostolic stewardship: he is completing the collection as a commissioned act, not an optional gesture. The task belongs to Christ; Paul is the agent of completion.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct: "I know that when I come to you, I will come in the full measure of the blessing of Christ." The blessing Paul anticipates is not his own spiritual energy but Christ\'s blessing flowing through an apostle. The "full measure" (<em>plērōmati eulogias</em>) echoes Paul\'s cosmic language elsewhere (Eph 1:23; 3:19) — the fullness that belongs to Christ overflowing into the community through his herald.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct: Paul urges prayer "by our Lord Jesus Christ and by the love of the Spirit." The Trinitarian structure of the appeal — Christ as Lord, the Spirit as the one whose love compels prayer, and God as the one addressed — is characteristic of Paul\'s mature theology (2 Cor 13:14; Eph 3:14-19). The intercession Paul requests is itself Trinitarian participation: praying through the Son, empowered by the Spirit, to the Father.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme: The specific prayer requests — protection from unbelievers in Judea and favorable reception of the collection by Jewish believers — are framed within the theological vision of Jew-Gentile unity in Christ (chs.9-11; 15:8-12). The "service" (<em>diakonia</em>) Paul wants accepted is the material expression of the unity Christ has created; its acceptance would be a concrete sign of that unity. The prayer stakes are Christological.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A theme: "That I may come to you with joy, by God\'s will, and in your company be refreshed" — Paul\'s desire for mutual encouragement reflects the reciprocity of the body of Christ (1:11-12). The joy and refreshment are not merely personal benefit but the joy of the gospel advancing and Christ\'s people strengthened together. "By God\'s will" is the apostolic recognition that the mission belongs to God; Paul plans but does not control the outcome.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A theme: "The God of peace be with you all. Amen." Peace is not a vague benediction here — it is the <em>eirēnē</em> that Paul established in 5:1 as the fruit of justification through Christ ("since we have been justified through faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ"). The God of peace is the God who achieved that peace through Christ\'s atoning death and validated it through his resurrection. The benediction summarizes the letter\'s gospel.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: Phoebe is commended as a <em>diakonos</em> (deacon/minister) of the church in Cenchreae. The term Paul uses is the same he applies to Christ in 15:8 (<em>diakonon peritomēs</em>) — Christ the minister, Phoebe the minister, both serving within Christ\'s commissioned work. The church at Cenchreae, gathering "in Christ," is one of the communities formed by the gospel Paul has been expounding throughout the letter.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: Receiving Phoebe "in the Lord in a way worthy of his people" — the <em>axios tōn hagiōn</em> (worthy of the saints) standard is the dignity that belongs to those who are in Christ. Her status as <em>prostatis</em> (benefactor/patron) of many, including Paul, demonstrates that the communal economy of the body of Christ inverts patron-client hierarchies: leadership serves, and the one who has resources deploys them for others.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: Priscilla and Aquila, "co-workers in Christ Jesus," are greeted with the designation that defines all apostolic collaboration: the work is Christ\'s, and all who labor in it are co-workers under him. Their risking of their lives for Paul (v.4) is the cruciform pattern of the body of Christ enacted — each member willing to bear the burden another cannot carry alone (15:1).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Not only I but all the churches of the Gentiles are grateful to them." The gratitude of the Gentile churches to two Jewish believers who risked their lives reflects the Jew-Gentile unity in Christ that Paul has argued throughout chs.9-15. The practical solidarity across ethnic lines is the embodied form of the theological argument: in Christ the dividing wall has been broken down (Eph 2:14).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct: Epaenetus is called "the firstfruits of Achaia to Christ" — <em>aparchē tēs Asias eis Christon</em>. The firstfruits language (cf. 8:23; 11:16; 1 Cor 15:20) frames the first convert of a region as a pledge and foretaste of the full harvest to come: if the firstfruits are holy, so is the whole batch (11:16). Each region\'s first convert stands as a type of the full ingathering that Christ\'s resurrection has made possible.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: Mary "worked very hard" for the Roman community — <em>ekopiasen</em>, the word Paul uses for apostolic labor (1 Cor 15:10; Gal 4:11). The same verb applied to Paul\'s own missionary toil is applied to Mary\'s work for the community. In Christ\'s body the labor of building up the community is shared work, regardless of gender or social status. The one who labors is serving Christ (Col 3:23-24).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct: Andronicus and Junia are "in Christ before I was" — the priority of being "in Christ" is the fundamental marker of belonging to the new community. Paul\'s own conversion was not the beginning of the church; the resurrection appearances came first, and others were incorporated into Christ before Paul. The phrase "in Christ" as a temporal reference treats union with Christ as the defining event of existence.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: Ampliatus is "my dear friend in the Lord" — <em>agapētos mou en Kyriō</em>. The friendship is constituted in the Lord; the bond is not merely personal affinity but sharing in Christ. The love that Paul earlier described as flowing from God through Christ (5:5; 8:35, 39) is now expressed in the specific warmth of fraternal greeting. The Lord is the medium and ground of the relationship.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: Urbanus is "our co-worker in Christ" — the same collaborative designation as Priscilla and Aquila (v.3). All apostolic co-workers participate in a shared labor whose ultimate agent is Christ. The repetition of "in Christ" as the frame for naming these relationships reinforces the Christological grammar of the entire community: identity, relationship, and vocation are all located in Christ.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: Apelles is "whose fidelity to Christ has stood the test" — <em>ton dokimon en Christō</em>, the approved one in Christ. The testing and approval Paul commends (cf. 5:3-4; 2 Cor 2:9) is specifically Christological: fidelity under pressure that proves genuine belonging to Christ. The household of Aristobulus represents a household network that includes Christ-followers, the church extending into the social fabric of Roman households.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: Herodion is "my fellow Jew" — Paul uses <em>suggenē</em> (kinsman), the term he used for all Israel in 9:3. The greeting embeds the Jew-Gentile reality of the Roman church: some are kin by blood (<em>suggeneis</em>), all are kin in Christ. The household of Narcissus "who are in the Lord" — not all the household, but those within it who belong to Christ — illustrates the church\'s penetration of existing social structures without replacing them.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: Tryphena, Tryphosa, and Persis all "work hard in the Lord" — the verb <em>kopiaō</em> again, the word for toiling in the Lord\'s service. The accumulation of named women who labor in the community (Mary in v.6, now three more) reflects the household church context of early Christianity, where the labor of building community fell on all members. The Lord in whose service they labor is Christ, and their toil participates in his ongoing work of forming his people.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct: Rufus is "chosen in the Lord" — <em>eklekton en Kyriō</em>. The election language (cf. 8:33; 9:11; 11:5) applied to an individual names him as one of those God foreknew and predestined to be conformed to Christ\'s image (8:29). His mother\'s mothering of Paul illustrates the way the community of the elect in Christ forms family bonds that transcend biological ties — Christ reconstitutes kinship around himself (Mark 3:34-35).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: The cluster of names — Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, Hermas, and the brothers and sisters with them — represents a house church gathering in Christ. The plural "brothers and sisters with them" indicates a network of believers assembled around these individuals. Each name represents a person incorporated into the body of Christ, and Paul\'s individual greeting treats each one as significant within that body — no member unnamed or overlooked.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme: A second house church cluster — Philologus, Julia, Nereus and his sister, Olympas, and "all the Lord\'s people with them." The "Lord\'s people" (<em>tous hagious</em>, the saints) is Paul\'s standard term for those consecrated to God through Christ (1:7; 15:25-26). The greeting to all the saints in each house church reflects the unity of the one body across multiple gathering places — one Lord, one body, many assemblies.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct: "Greet one another with a holy kiss. All the churches of Christ send greetings." The holy kiss is a ritual of the community gathered in Christ — a physical expression of the bond that Christ creates among those who belong to him. The "churches of Christ" (<em>hai ekklēsiai pasai tou Christou</em>) naming the network of communities by their possession by Christ: they are Christ\'s churches, gathered by him and belonging to him across the Roman world.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct: The warning to watch out for those causing divisions "contrary to the teaching you have learned" is a warning about departing from the Christ-centered gospel Paul has expounded. The "teaching" (<em>didachē</em>) they received is the apostolic proclamation of Jesus as Lord (10:9) and the gospel of God concerning his Son (1:2-4). Division from that teaching is division from Christ himself; the obstacles placed in the way are obstacles to the obedience of faith (1:5; 16:26) that Christ requires.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct: "For such people are not serving our Lord Christ (<em>tō Kyriō Christō</em>) but their own appetites." The explicit naming — "our Lord Christ" — specifies the one whose service is the standard. Those who use smooth words to serve themselves have effectively transferred their service from Christ to the self, inverting the cruciform pattern Christ established and that Paul has been arguing throughout the letter.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "Everyone has heard about your obedience" — the Roman believers\' obedience is the <em>hypakoē pisteōs</em>, the obedience that comes from faith (1:5; 16:26), the response to Christ that Paul was commissioned to produce among the Gentiles. The commendation is Christological: their obedience is the fruit of the gospel Paul proclaimed, and its fame is the evidence that Christ\'s apostolic work through Paul has been effective in Rome.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct: "The God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet." Paul applies Genesis 3:15 — the protoevangelium — to the present moment: the serpent-crushing promised to the seed of the woman is enacted through Christ\'s victory over sin and death (5:12-21; 8:3), and that victory is extended to Christ\'s people who inherit his conquest. "Under your feet" (Ps 8:6; 110:1) draws on the royal language applied to Christ\'s resurrection-exaltation — those in Christ share his victory over the adversary. "The grace of our Lord Jesus be with you" ties the victory to the same Lord who achieved it.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme: Timothy, Lucius, Jason, and Sosipater — named as "my fellow Jews" (Paul\'s kinsmen by race) and "my co-worker" (Timothy, sharing the apostolic labor) — extend greetings that connect Rome to the broader network of Jewish and Gentile believers laboring in Christ. The greetings from diaspora across the eastern Mediterranean reinforce that the Roman community belongs to one universal network constituted by Christ, not by geography or ethnicity.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: Tertius, "who wrote down this letter," greets the recipients "in the Lord." The scribe\'s self-identification is brief but significant: even the amanuensis who took Paul\'s dictation participates in the ministry and addresses the recipients within the relational framework of the Lord. The letter itself — the vehicle of the apostolic gospel — is mediated through a member of the body of Christ who takes his place in the community his labor helped produce.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme: Gaius, Erastus, and Quartus extend the greetings from Corinth to Rome. Gaius\'s hospitality — hosting both Paul and "the whole church here" — exemplifies the community of the body of Christ expressed in material provision. Erastus, the city\'s director of public works, represents the penetration of Christ\'s community into civic life. The breadth of names across social strata — civic official, church host, unnamed "brother" — reflects the Christological community that cuts across social hierarchy.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct: "May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with all of you." This grace benediction closes the letter\'s personal section with the same Christological source with which it opened (1:7: "Grace and peace to you from God our Father and from the Lord Jesus Christ"). The grace is specifically Christ\'s grace — the unmerited favor that constitutes and sustains the entire community Paul has been addressing.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct: "Now to him who is able to establish you in accordance with my gospel, the message I proclaim about Jesus Christ, in keeping with the revelation of the mystery hidden for long ages past." The doxological climax of the letter is explicitly Christological: the power to establish the Roman believers is the same power that raised Christ from the dead (1:4); the gospel is the message "about Jesus Christ"; and the mystery hidden for ages is now revealed in him. Paul\'s entire letter is summarized in this attributive phrase — the gospel of Jesus Christ as the revealed mystery of God\'s eternal purpose.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct: "But now revealed and made known through the prophetic writings by the command of the eternal God, so that all the Gentiles might come to the obedience that comes from faith." The prophetic writings that now disclose the mystery are the OT scriptures read in light of Christ\'s life, death, and resurrection — the same Scriptures Paul has been citing throughout the letter (from Gen 15 to Isa 52) as witnesses to the gospel. The goal of the revelation is the <em>hypakoē pisteōs</em> among all Gentiles — the obedience of faith that Paul was commissioned to produce (1:5), now named again as the eschatological purpose of the revealed mystery. The mystery is Christ; the obedience is the world\'s response to Christ.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct: "To the only wise God be glory forever through Jesus Christ! Amen." The doxology is a complete theological statement: God alone possesses wisdom (the mystery that puzzled the ages is his eternal plan); glory belongs to him forever; and the channel of that glory is <em>dia Iēsou Christou</em> — through Jesus Christ. Christ is not merely the content of the gospel but the medium through whom God is glorified. The letter that began with the revelation of God\'s righteousness in Christ (1:17; 3:21-26) ends with glory ascending to God through Christ — the circle of grace and doxology complete.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'romans')
    merge_comm(existing, ROMANS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'romans', existing)
    print('Romans 15–16 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
